rainsber@... wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; Step 1: Try to test the *feature* and not just each method. That might
&gt; solve your problem, by giving you a natural name for those tests.
&gt; 
&gt; As an example, when I test that my data model class handles a data store
&gt; with no widgets in it, I generally write a test like:
&gt; 
&gt; testNoWidgets() {
&gt;     MockDataModel model = new MockDataModel();    // MockDataModel extends
&gt; DataModel
&gt;     model.ensureNoWidgets();    // special method on mock data model to let
&gt; me &quot;sneak in&quot; and change things.
&gt; 
&gt;     // Test public interface of DataModel when there are no widgets.
&gt;     assertEquals(0, model.countWidgets());
&gt; 
&gt;     assertTrue(model.collectAllWidgets().isEmpty());
&gt; 
&gt;     assertTrue(model.collectAllWidgets(new WidgetFilter() {
&gt;         public void accept(Widget each) {
&gt;             // Accept all widgets.
&gt;         }
&gt;     }).isEmpty());
&gt; 
&gt;     model.eachWidget(new WidgetBlock() {
&gt;         public void execute(Widget each) {
&gt;             fail(&quot;How did I get here?!&quot;);
&gt;         }
&gt;     });
&gt;     ...
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Notice that I create a scenario, then test each method under that scenario.
&gt; This is an inverse view from writing a separate test for each method, then
&gt; varying the scenarios.
&gt; 
&gt; Step 2: If Step 1 fails because you can&#39;t figure out a good way to do it,
&gt; then there is no &quot;rule&quot;. I would suggest naming the test methods by what
&gt; the method under test *does* and not its signature.
&gt; 
&gt; testEngineDigestReturnsEmptyBuffer() {
&gt;     // simulate/set up empty buffer...
&gt;     assertNotNull(&quot;engineDigest() returned null?!&quot;, myObject.engineDigest
&gt; ());
&gt;     assertEquals(0, myObject.engineDigest().length);
&gt; }
&gt; ...
&gt; testEngineDigestAcceptsEmptyBuffer() {
&gt;     assertEquals(0, engineDigest(new byte[0], 0, 0));
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; You would have similar tests for buffers of different sizes, contents, or
&gt; whatever variables might change, given the feature you&#39;re trying to
&gt; implement.
